node.text: Cynthia DiBartolo’s journey to the New York Stock Exchange floor was fraught with challenges and difficulty. In July 2021, DiBartolo’s firm, Tigress Financial Partners, became the first disabled and woman-owned floor broker to become a member of the NYSE. Prior to launching Tigress Financial in 2011, DiBartolo served as a compliance director, an attorney, and as a risk management director for some of Wall Streets’ largest firms. However, her life would change in 2009 with a diagnosis of throat and neck cancer. DiBartolo became severely disabled following life-saving surgery that compromised her ability to eat, speak and swallow. But inspiration from her father convinced her that she needed to act; “They took your tongue, not your brain.” her father told her. Using her experience from decades on Wall Street and tenacity DiBartolo launched the first and nation’s only disabled and woman-owned financial services firm.

node.title: The 1st disabled and woman-owned NYSE floor broker is changing Wall Street

node.text: Being a millionaire may be more common than you think. About 20 million people in the U.S. have enough assets to fit the definition, according to a 2020 study by Credit Suisse. Chris Hogan, author of the book “Everyday Millionaires,” surveyed more than 10,000 of those wealthy individuals to figure out their secret to success. Having a particular mindset almost universally contributed to millionaires’ success, Hogan said. He found that around 97% of millionaires surveyed believed they were in control of their own destiny. That is much higher than the 55% of the general population Hogan found to hold the same opinion. Check out this video to see the other four beliefs and practices that more than 90% of millionaires apply to their money.

node.title: More than 90% of millionaires used these five tools to build wealth

node.text: Americans are funding their retirement accounts at record rates. But figuring out how much your monthly contributions will be worth in a few decades can be confusing. node.text: Investments in farmland are growing across the country as people, including the ultra-wealthy like Bill Gates, look for new ways to grow their money. In 2020, Gates made headlines for becoming the largest private farmland owner in the U.S. He had accumulated more than 269,000 acres of farmland across 18 states in less than a decade. His farmland grows onions, carrots and even the potatoes that are used to make McDonald’s french fries. How is he making money off of farmland in the U.S.? Watch the video to find out.

node.text: Porsche is in the minds of many the ultimate sports car brand. Its cars – especially its legendary 911 – blend high performance with quality construction and even a solid reputation for dependability. But the brand that made its name with small nimble two-door sports cars ruffled feathers in the automotive world when it tried its hand at a four-door sport utility vehicle, the Cayenne. Today, SUVs make up a huge chunk of Porsche’s sales. The brand is now entering the race toward electrification – but this time the innovator is playing catch-up to others.

node.title: How Porsche went from sports cars to SUVs ... and EVs

node.text:
Amazon is bringing its automated checkout technology to a pair of Whole Foods stores, the company announced Wednesday, marking the latest test of the grab-and-go system in a full-size supermarket.⁠
⁠
Amazon’s “Just Walk Out” technology allows shoppers to enter a store by scanning an app and exit without needing to stand in a checkout line. Cameras and sensors track what items shoppers select and charge them when they leave.⁠
⁠
Which two Whole Foods stores will have the technology? Link in bio for more details.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on September 07, 2021. May be an image of standing and text that says 'Tech giants are rushing to develop their own chips CNBC'.

node.text:
Not content with relying on standard chips that are in high demand, some of the world’s biggest tech firms are developing their own semiconductors.⁠
⁠
Apple, Amazon, Facebook, Tesla and Baidu are all shunning established chip firms and bringing certain aspects of chip development in-house. At present, barely a month goes by without a Big Tech company announcing a new chip project.⁠
⁠
Why are these firms thinking twice about where they get their chips from? Find out at the link in bio.

Over the years, Amazon has built up an army of warehouses, shipping hubs, delivery vans and trucks to ensure it can meet its Prime pledge of delivery in two days or less.⁠
⁠
Amazon’s air fleet, which now has 75 planes, is another increasingly critical component of the company’s logistics machine. The fleet gives Amazon greater control over its own packages and enables it to offer even faster deliveries.⁠
⁠
Read about how this is bringing Amazon into direct competition with FedEx and UPS at the link in bio.

node.text:
“People have said we’re going to eliminate or eradicate the virus. No, we’re not, very, very unlikely.”⁠
⁠
Covid-19 is likely “here to stay with us” as the virus continues to mutate in unvaccinated countries across the world and previous hopes of eradicating it diminish, global health officials said Tuesday.⁠
⁠
Read about why the situation today could have been very different if the world had taken early steps to stop the spread of the virus at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on September 07, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'Pfizer Covid booster shots will likely be ready Sept. 20, but Moderna may be delayed, Fauci says CNBC'.

node.text:
The U.S. will likely start to widely distribute Pfizer Covid-19 booster shots during the week of Sept. 20, but the rollout for Moderna’s vaccine could be delayed, White House chief medical advisor Dr. Anthony Fauci said Sunday.⁠
⁠
The Biden administration has announced plans to offer third doses to people who received the Pfizer and Moderna shots, pending approval from public health officials. The U.S. recommends an additional shot eight months after the second dose.⁠
⁠
Why may those who received Moderna shots have to wait a bit longer? Find out at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on September 07, 2021. May be an image of money and text that says 'El Salvador bought $21 million of bitcoin as it becomes first country to make it a legal currency PEER मष्ट CNBC'.

node.text:
El Salvador bought roughly $20.9 million worth of bitcoin, one day before it formally adopts the world’s most popular cryptocurrency as legal tender. ⁠
⁠
President Nayib Bukele revealed that the country had purchased a total of 400 bitcoin, the first step in a larger push to add the digital currency to its balance sheet. Bukele’s announcement marks a major milestone for bitcoin. El Salvador is now the first country to have officially put bitcoin on its balance sheet and hold it in its reserves.⁠
⁠
But El Salvador's bitcoin law has drawn criticism across the country. Find out why at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on September 06, 2021. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'This 35-year-old left the U.S. for Croatia and lives on $47 a day CNBC'.

node.text:
@CNBCMakeIt contributor Steve Tsentserensky moved to Croatia after the country announced that it would start offering a one-year residence permit to digital nomads in January 2021.⁠
⁠
He currently lives by himself in a 650-square-foot apartment in Split, Croatia’s second-largest city, and only spends an average of $47 a day to live there.⁠
⁠
How does he manage to spend so little? Read a breakdown of his expenses at the link in bio.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on September 06, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'An 80-year-old doctor and longevity expert shares his 5 habits for a longer life: 'It's never too late to start' CNBC'.

node.text:
If you could prolong your life by a few more years (or even live to be 100), would you do it? @CNBCMakeIt contributor Dr. Richard W. Besdine can't think of many people who would say no.⁠
⁠
Having been a geriatrician for 55 years, the one question Besdine is constantly asked — by folks of all ages — is, "What are the most important everyday habits that can lead to a longer, more vibrant life?" ⁠
⁠
Link in bio for what he says you can do now to increase your chances of living a longer, healthier life.

node.text:
Hiring has perhaps never been harder for employers.⁠
⁠
As pandemic restrictions eased amid the accessibility of Covid vaccines and businesses started bouncing back, many employers faced workforce shortages. The competition to recruit new workers as well as retain existing ones is now fierce. To try to counteract that, companies of all sizes are trying to attract workers with increased pay.⁠
⁠
However, just increasing pay alone won’t be enough for businesses to compete for workers. Find out why at the link in bio.

node.text:
Jamaican sprinter Usain Bolt is still known as the fastest man alive and one of the richest athletes.⁠
⁠
But Bolt, 34, admits he wasn’t always good with his money. ⁠
⁠
The biggest lesson the world's fastest man says he learned is to save more than half of your earnings: “Then you can spend the rest and pay bills. I tell people if you make $10, save $6, and then you can figure out what to do with the rest.”⁠
⁠
Read about the money advice Bolt would give his younger self at the link in bio. (With @CNBCMakeIt)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by CNBC on September 05, 2021. May be an image of sky and text that says 'These 5 traits set extraordinary people apart, says former FBI agent "but you need the entire set" CNBC'.

node.text:
What makes someone extraordinary? ⁠
⁠
Surprisingly, the qualities that make these people stand out aren’t related to their level of education, income or talents (say, in athletics or art or business).⁠
⁠
As it turns out, based on thousands of observations, there are five traits that set exceptional individuals apart from everyone else — but you must have the entire set, and not just one or a few.⁠
⁠
Find out if you have these traits at the link in bio. (With @CNBCMakeIt)
